'''Ole Arntzen''' (4 February 1910 &ndash; 7 August 1973) was a Norwegian businessman and resistance member during World War II. He was a brother of [[Sven Arntzen]]. He was a member of the Central Committee of [[Milorg]], where he served as General Inspector ("Stor I") from April 1944 to May 1945.<ref name=kl>{{cite encyclopedia |first=Ivar |last=Kraglund |authorlink=Ivar Kraglund | encyclopedia=[[Norsk krigsleksikon 1940-45]] |title=Arntzen, Ole |language=Norwegian |editor=[[Hans Fredrik Dahl|Dahl]] |editor2=[[Guri Hjeltnes|Hjeltnes]] |editor3=[[Berit Nøkleby|Nøkleby]] |editor4=[[Nils Johan Ringdal|Ringdal]] |editor5=[[Øystein Sørensen|Sørensen]] |url= |accessdate= |year=1995 |publisher=Cappelen |location=Oslo |isbn=82-02-14138-9 |page=30 }}</ref><ref name=jch>{{cite book |title=Jens Chr. Hauge &ndash; fullt og helt |first=Olav |last=Njølstad |authorlink=Olav Njølstad |pages=153–155 |publisher=Aschehoug |language=Norwegian |location=Oslo |year=2008 |isbn=978-82-03-22988-6 }}</ref> His cover name was "Ørnulf". In his World War II memoirs, [[Gunnar Sønsteby]] devotes one chapter to the arrest of Milorg leaders [[Jens Christian Hauge]] and Arntzen by the [[Statspolitiet|State police]] on 10 April 1945, but their central role was not discovered.<ref name=report24>{{cite book |title=Rapport fra "Nr. 24"|first=Gunnar |last=Sønsteby |authorlink=Gunnar Sønsteby |chapter=Milorg-ledelsen arrestert! |year=1960 |pages=246–249 |publisher=Ernst G. Mortensen |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

